 surname is rare in Britain."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William de Miners was born about 1125 as the son of Roger de Miners. He married Agnes of Burghill in 1145, in Burghill, Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died about 1200, in Burghill, Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 77."},"et":{"Abt 1125–about 1200":"umbes 1125–umbes 1200","1125–1200":"1125–1200","1130–Male":"1130–Surnud","1120–Female":"1120–Surnud","1145–1217":"1145–1217","1105–1175":"1105–1175","1217":"1217","1105":"1105","ABT 1175":"umbes 1175","1125":"1125","1145":"1145","1200":"1200","1175":"1175","1120":"1120","about 1145":"umbes 1145","about 1200":"umbes 1200","1130":"1130","Abt 1125":"umbes 1125","Burghill, Herefordshire, England":"Burghill, Herefordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Westbury On Severn, Gloucestershire, England":"Westbury on Severn, Gloucestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1125–about 1200":"noin 1125–noin 1200","1125–1200":"1125–1200","1130–Male":"1130–Kuollut","1120–Female":"1120–Kuollut","1145–1217":"1145–1217","1105–1175":"1105–1175","1217":"1217","1105":"1105","ABT 1175":"noin 1175","1125":"1125","1145":"1145","1200":"1200","1175":"1175","1120":"1